SECTION 5 — AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE
Who they are:

Adults who have noticed nail discolouration, thickness, or brittleness and have either tried an OTC product that didn't work or are deciding whether to start. They range from people who just noticed something wrong (early stage, not sure if it's fungus) to people who have been dealing with it for months and are frustrated. Many have already spent money on OTC products with limited results. A significant subset is reluctant to see a doctor — either cost, access, or embarrassment. They are not medically trained. They want a clear answer, not clinical hedging.
What they want from this post:

A straight answer on what treatment options exist and which are most effective
To understand whether they need a prescription or can manage it themselves
To know what to expect in terms of timelines — how long before it gets better
Confidence in a decision: try this first, then escalate if X happens

What frustrates them:

Products that promise results and deliver nothing
Articles that list ten options without saying which one actually works
Being told "see a doctor" without any context for when that becomes necessary
Inconsistency between sources on whether OTC treatments do anything at all
Not understanding why nail fungus is so hard to clear compared to other infections

